>The verification part is strait forward.
>
>y_1 = 1/x
>
>hence
>
>y_1' = -1/x^2   and  y_1'' = 2/x^3
>
>Substitution gives:
>
>          2(4x^2 - x)   2(2x-1)   4
>     0 =  ----------- - ------- - -
>              x^3         x^2     x
>
>       = (8x^2 - 2x - 4x^2 + 2x - 4x^2)/x^3
>
>       = 0
>
>I think I can find a second lenearly independent solution with the 
>following formula:
>
>  y_2 = y_1 * int[2(2x - 1)/(4x^2 -x)]dx
>
>But I can't integrate this!!
>
>However once I have this second solution then I can compute a 
>Wronskian for y_1 and y_2 with the formula:
>
>     W(x) = y_1 * y_2' - y_2 * y_1'
